Ex 3:

t.test(nc$gained,mu=30,alternative=c("two.sided"), conf.level=0.95)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  nc$gained
## t = 0.7136, df = 972, p-value = 0.4756
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is not equal to 30
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  29.42985 31.22174
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##   30.3258
#The p value is bellow the alpha which means we reject the null hypothesis.

Ex 4:

# Null hypothesis is that the porportion of weight gained is 30 pounds. 
# Alternative hypothesis that porportion of weight gained is  less than 30 pounds. 
t.test(nc$gained,mu=30,alternative=c("less"), conf.level=0.94)
## 
##  One Sample t-test
## 
## data:  nc$gained
## t = 0.7136, df = 972, p-value = 0.7622
## alternative hypothesis: true mean is less than 30
## 94 percent confidence interval:
##      -Inf 31.03626
## sample estimates:
## mean of x 
##   30.3258
#the p value is above the alpha which means we acceapt the null hypothesis.

Ex 5:

#Null hypothesis that porpotion  of babies is not 5.5 pounds. 
# Alternative hypothesis is that porpotion  of babies is 5.5 pounds.

##  One Sample t-test

#The p value is below the alpha which means we reject the null hypothesis.

Ex 6:

#Null hypothesis that porpotion  of babies who weigh less than 5.5 pounds is 50%. 
# Alternative hypothesis is that the poprotion of babies who weigh less 5.5 pound is less than 50%
#the p value is above the alpha which means we acceapt the null hypothesis.
y=sum(nc$weight<5.5)
n=length(nc$weight)
prop.test(y,n,p=.5,alternative = "less",.95)
## 
##  1-sample proportions test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  y out of n, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 625.68, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true p is less than 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.0000000 0.1214932
## sample estimates:
##     p 
## 0.104

Ex 7:

#H0 The baby weight of the mother who smoke and dont smoke should be the same.

#H1 The baby weight of the mother who smoke and dont smoke should be the diffrent.

Ex 8:

attach(nc)
t.test(weight~habit)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  weight by habit
## t = 2.359, df = 171.32, p-value = 0.01945
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.05151165 0.57957328
## sample estimates:
## mean in group nonsmoker    mean in group smoker 
##                7.144273                6.828730
inference(y = nc$weight, x = nc$habit, est = "mean", type = "ht", null = 0, alternative = "twosided", method = "theoretical", order = c("smoker","nonsmoker"))
## Response variable: numerical, Explanatory variable: categorical
## Difference between two means
## Summary statistics:
## n_smoker = 126, mean_smoker = 6.8287, sd_smoker = 1.3862
## n_nonsmoker = 873, mean_nonsmoker = 7.1443, sd_nonsmoker = 1.5187
## Observed difference between means (smoker-nonsmoker) = -0.3155
## H0: mu_smoker - mu_nonsmoker = 0 
## HA: mu_smoker - mu_nonsmoker != 0 
## Standard error = 0.134 
## Test statistic: Z =  -2.359 
## p-value =  0.0184

# It seems that non smoker and smokers have babys different body weight. We reject the null hypothesis because the p value is above the null and we support the alternative hypothesis.

inference(y = nc$weight, x = nc$habit, est = "mean", type = "ci", null = 0, alternative = "twosided", method = "theoretical", order = c("smoker","nonsmoker"))

## Standard error = 0.1338 
## 95 % Confidence interval = ( -0.5777 , -0.0534 )
# The confidence interval shows that there is a diffrence between the weight of babies of smoker and non smokers.

inference(y=nc$weight, x=nc$mature, est = "mean", type= "ht", null = 0, alternative = "twosided", method = "theoretical",conflevel = 0.95)
## Response variable: numerical, Explanatory variable: categorical
## Difference between two means
## Summary statistics:
## n_mature mom = 133, mean_mature mom = 7.1256, sd_mature mom = 1.6591
## n_younger mom = 867, mean_younger mom = 7.0972, sd_younger mom = 1.4855
## Observed difference between means (mature mom-younger mom) = 0.0283
## H0: mu_mature mom - mu_younger mom = 0 
## HA: mu_mature mom - mu_younger mom != 0 
## Standard error = 0.152 
## Test statistic: Z =  0.186 
## p-value =  0.8526

# The p value is greater than the alpha meaning we acceapt the null hypothesis that mature and younger moms gain the same weight.

5:

#Hypothesis
# I am seeing the effect of gender on the weight of babies.
# Null Hypothesis: I believe that males and females babies will weight the same.
#Alternative Hypothesis: I believe that weight of males and females will be different.
inference(y = nc$weight, x=nc$gender, est = "mean", type = "ci", null = 0, alternative = "twosided",method = "theoretical", order = c("male","female"))
## Response variable: numerical, Explanatory variable: categorical
## Difference between two means
## Summary statistics:
## n_male = 497, mean_male = 7.3015, sd_male = 1.5168
## n_female = 503, mean_female = 6.9029, sd_female = 1.4759

## Observed difference between means (male-female) = 0.3986
## Standard error = 0.0947 
## 95 % Confidence interval = ( 0.2131 , 0.5841 )
# The data disproves my null hypothesis as the confidence interval shows that the weight of males and females will be different.
